    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1941-02-13T11:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1941-02-13T11:00:00-05:00" n="931"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d931">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.0011 European War 1939/8361: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Yugoslavia</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Lane</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Belgrade</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1941-02-13T17:00:00+01:00"
                            >February 13, 1941—5 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received February 14—6:30 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>96. Department’s 21.<note n="25" xml:id="d931fn25">Dated February 9, 10 p.m.,
                            <ref target="#pg_941">p. 941</ref>.</note> In talks today with officials
                    I learned that our position as stated by Department to Bulgarian Minister and by
                        MacMurray<note n="26" xml:id="d931fn26">John Van A. MacMurray, Ambassador in
                        Turkey.</note> and me in Ankara and here had made strong impression.</p>
                <p>One very important official said that our action might yet dissuade Bulgaria
                    provided that Bulgaria wished to be dissuaded. As to Yugoslavia and Turkey he
                    said that our attitude is discouraging: Officially we say that we do not intend
                    to enter war, yet unofficially we advise small countries to resist. I replied
                    that if United States were threatened with invasion we would certainly resist
                    and that we are not suggesting to Yugoslavia or any other country to take
                    offensive action. Again I emphasized reasons for helping Britain, China and
                    Greece. He said Bulgarian situation is still critical but worst may still be
                    averted. Further comments in my 97.<note n="27" xml:id="d931fn27">Not
                        printed.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Lane</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
